{
  "text": "As the adverse effects of total, trans and saturated fat intake contrasts with the beneficial effects of other fats (including the long chain omega-3 (n \u00c0 3) fatty acids, which may have antitumourigenic properties; [CITATION_1] , detailed analyses of the type and source of fat intake in relation to EOC risk according to the histologic subtype are needed. In this large population-based case-control study of ovarian cancer, we evaluated different sources and types of fat consumption in relation to risk of EOC overall and its major histologic subtypes.",
